>\n        <li><a href=\"#organization\">Organization</a></li>\n        <li><a href=\"#membership-guidelines\">Membership Guidelines</a></li>\n    </ul>\n</nav>		<h2>History</h2><p>As the Southeast Asian region has been facing critical challenges in their economic, societal, and political sectors, there has been a need to gather experts and educators to exchange ideas and face shared challenges. The excellence of universities is an important key to enhance a nation\'s competitiveness. Therefore, President Chiang Kao of the National Cheng Kung University (NCKU), Taiwan, together with the Presidents of prestigious universities of Southeast Asian countries initiated the \"Presidents\' Forum of Southeast Asia and Taiwan Universities\" (abbreviated as SATU Presidents\' Forum) in the year 2003.</p><p>This forum provides a venue for academics to share their valuable experiences to improve higher education and international cooperation in the region. The International Secretariat of the SATU Presidents\' Forum, which includes the two subsections named Academic Exchange Subcommittee and Industry Academia Collaboration Subcommittee, has been established at NCKU to coordinate and to promote the related activities.</p><h2>Objectives</h2><p>SATU Presidents\' Forum will be held biennially to achieve the following objectives:</p><ul><li>To strengthen academic cooperation among Taiwan and Southeast and South Asian countries.</li><li>To foster internationalization through academic and cultural exchange and collaboration.</li><li>To promote the quality of education, research and community services.</li><li>To establish exchange programs for our universities\' students, faculty and administrative staff.</li><li>To foster partnerships between industry and academia.</li><li>To facilitate sustainability in economics, society and the environment.</li></ul><h2>Organization</h2><h3>SATU Presidents\' Forum</h3><p><strong>Chairperson:</strong></p><p>Professor Shireesh B. Kedare, Director, Indian Institute of Technology Bombay, India (IITB)</p><p>Professor Milind Atrey, Deputy Director of Academics, Research and Translation, Indian Institute of Technology Bombay, India (IITB)</p><h3>Steering Committee</h3><p>Please refer to <a href=\"/steering-committee\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">the Steering Committee Section</a> for the incumbent Steering Committee Members.</p><h3>International Secretariat</h3><p><strong>Secretary General:</strong></p><p>Professor Sudarshan Kumar, Dean International Relations, IITB</p><p><strong>Executive Secretary:</strong></p><p>Ms. Rebecca Jadin, Project Manager, Office of International Relations, IITB</p><h2>Membership Guidelines</h2><h3>Eligibility</h3><p>Renowned universities of Southeast and South Asia countries and Taiwan who are interested in the development of enhanced cooperation with other universities in these regions are eligible for membership in the SATU Presidents\' Forum.</p><h3>To Join SATU</h3><p>Send the request for membership in SATU to the International Secretariat. The annual Steering Committee meeting has full and final discretion to decide whether to admit a new member. Admission is approved upon the consent of a majority of the Steering Committee members. When matters of necessity arise, the Committee can make decisions by voting through the circulation of a formal document.</p><h3>Term of Membership</h3><p>Membership in SATU is biennial in its cycle, requiring the payment of dues every other year. The membership term starts on August 1 of the year of membership renewal and expires on July 31 of the following year. For members admitted starting from the second year of a regular biennial membership period (even-numbered years), the membership term starts on August 1 of the admission year and expires on July 31 of the same year.</p><h3>Membership Fee</h3><p>The biennial membership fee is USD 600. If a member is admitted starting from the second year of a regular biennial membership period (even-numbered years), a pro rata membership fee of the member concerned for the first year is USD 300, and then USD 600 when the new biennial membership cycle begins. The International Secretariat will send notifications of membership dues biennially. The payment of the biennial dues shall constitute formal recognition of membership. The payment notice and reminders would be sent to members according to the following schedule:</p><table><thead><tr><th>Month</th><th>Action</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>August</td><td>Issuance of the membership fee payment notice</td></tr><tr><td>End of September</td><td>Issuance of the first membership fee payment reminder</td></tr><tr><td>January</td><td>Final deadline for membership fee payment</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Membership Benefits</h3><ul><li>Membership benefits include voting in elections at the General Assembly or voting through correspondence.</li><li>Members of SATU are entitled to be elected to serve on the Steering Committee.</li><li>Members can participate in activities held by SATU without registration charges, including the SATU Intensive Program, Joint Research Scheme, fellowship programs, and so forth. Some activities are open to members only.</li><li>Travel expenses and/or accommodations for the participation of SATU members in General Assembly and Steering Committee Meeting will be partly covered.</li><li>Various forms of support will be offered to member university scholars who participate in major SATU events.</li><li>With the consensus among Steering Committee members, the SATU International Secretariat will conduct surveys on academic information/activities of member universities, and circulate the findings among member and observer universities.</li></ul>','About SATU','','inherit','closed','closed','','57-revision-v1','','','2026-05-20 20:13:53','2026-05-20 20:13:53','',57,'http://10.18.33.196/?p=68',0,'revision','',0),
